  "excerpt": "The seventh-gen iPad Mini is on sale for just $399 ($100 off) at Amazon and Best Buy right now, which is the lowest price we’ve seen on Apple’s diminutive tablet.",
  "siteName": "The Verge",
  "favicon": "https://www.theverge.com/icons/android_chrome_512x512.png",
  "text": "If you’re in the market for a highly portable tablet, Apple’s smallest tablet has fallen to its lowest price to date at multiple retailers. Right now, the latest iPad Mini is on sale at Amazon and Best Buy with Wi-Fi and 128GB of storage starting at $399 ($100 off). If you need more storage, you can also buy the step-up model with 256GB of storage for $499 ($100 off) or the 512GB variant for $699 ($100 off).With its 8.3-inch screen and lightweight design, the latest iPad Mini is closer in size to the iPhone than any other tablet in Apple’s lineup. As a result, it’s easier to carry on the go and hold with one hand, making it an excellent option if you read a lot on your tablet. Its small size doesn’t come at the expense of performance, though. In fact, the onboard A17 Pro chip is snappier than the A14 Bionic chip found in the entry-level iPad, even if it’s not as speedy as the processors in the M4-powered iPad Pro or M2-powered Air.Unlike the base iPad, the seventh-gen Mini supports Apple Intelligence, so you can take advantage of a host of AI-based features — such as AI-assisted summaries, Genmoji, ChatGPT, and the ability to erase unwanted objects in photos. It also supports the newer Apple Pencil Pro, along with Wi-Fi 6E and faster USB-C performance. They’re pretty iterative updates overall; however, they’re also a lot more appealing at $399 than they are at the tablet’s typical retail price of $499.Read our iPad Mini review.The seventh-gen iPad Mini comes with Apple’s A17 Pro chip and support for Apple Intelligence. It’s also compatible with the Apple Pencil Pro and offers faster Wi-Fi and USB-C speeds.",
  "image": "https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/AQT-dsq01tcKLhx02-RVKWHdQDM=/0x0:4230x2826/1200x628/filters:focal(2410x1410:2411x1411)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25691635/iPad_Mini_8.jpg",
  "html": "\u003cdiv id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"\u003e\u003cdiv id=\"zephr-anchor\"\u003e\u003cp\u003eIf you’re in the market for a highly portable tablet, Apple’s smallest tablet has fallen to its lowest price to date at multiple retailers. Right now, the latest \u003cstrong\u003eiPad Mini \u003c/strong\u003eis on sale at \u003ca href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DK3YF38G?tag=theverge02-20\"\u003eAmazon\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca href=\"https://howl.link/38did5ox47dse\"\u003eBest Buy\u003c/a\u003e with Wi-Fi and 128GB of storage starting at $399 ($100 off). If you need more storage, you can also buy the step-up model with 256GB of storage \u003ca href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DK3WGKKB?tag=theverge02-20\"\u003efor $499 ($100 off)\u003c/a\u003e or the 512GB variant \u003ca href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DK3XHBH9?tag=theverge02-20\"\u003efor $699 ($100 off)\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eWith its 8.3-inch screen and lightweight design, the latest iPad Mini is closer in size to the iPhone than any other tablet in Apple’s lineup. As a result, it’s easier to carry on the go and hold with one hand, making it an excellent option if you read a lot on your tablet. Its small size doesn’t come at the expense of performance, though. In fact, the onboard A17 Pro chip is snappier than the A14 Bionic chip found in the \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/23418039/apple-ipad-review-10th-gen-2022-10-9-tablet-ipados\"\u003eentry-level iPad\u003c/a\u003e, even if it’s not as speedy as the processors in the \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24155440/apple-ipad-pro-2024-review\"\u003eM4-powered iPad Pro\u003c/a\u003e or \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/24155407/apple-ipad-air-review-2024\"\u003eM2-powered Air\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eUnlike the base iPad, the seventh-gen Mini supports \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/28/24279804/apple-intelligence-ios-18-1-siri-ai\"\u003eApple Intelligence\u003c/a\u003e, so you can take advantage of a host of AI-based features — such as AI-assisted summaries, \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/6/10/24175523/apple-ai-custom-emoji-images-ios18-wwdc\"\u003eGenmoji\u003c/a\u003e, \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/12/11/24317119/ios-18-2-apple-intelligence-chatgpt-genmoji\"\u003eChatGPT\u003c/a\u003e, and the ability to erase unwanted objects in photos. It also supports the \u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/5/7/24146454/apple-pencil-pro-ipad-stylus-price-availability-features\"\u003enewer Apple Pencil Pro\u003c/a\u003e, along with Wi-Fi 6E and faster USB-C performance. They’re pretty iterative updates overall; however, they’re also a lot more appealing at $399 than they are at the tablet’s typical retail price of $499.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ch5\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/22/24275956/apple-ipad-mini-2024-review\"\u003eRead our iPad Mini review.\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/h5\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\u003cdiv\u003e\u003cp\u003e\u003ca data-item-id=\"WLqz0Q\" href=\"https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DK3YF38G?tag=theverge02-20\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"A photo of the iPad Mini on a coffee table.\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-nimg=\"fill\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 300px\" srcset=\"https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:4240x2832/376x376/filters:focal(2120x1416:2121x1417):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25691621/iPad_Mini_1.jpg 376w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:4240x2832/384x384/filters:focal(2120x1416:2121x1417):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25691621/iPad_Mini_1.jpg 384w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:4240x2832/415x415/filters:focal(2120x1416:2121x1417):format(webp)/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_asset/file/25691621/iPad_Mini_1.jpg 415w, https://duet-cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/0x0:4240x2832/480x480/filters:focal(2120x1416:2121x1417):format(w